WEBVTT

00:19.620 --> 00:20.740
CHAPTER III

00:20.740 --> 00:25.160
When I had attained the age of seventeen, my parents resolved that I should become a

00:25.160 --> 00:27.400
student at the University of Ingolstadt.

00:27.960 --> 00:33.160
I had hitherto attended the schools of Geneva, but my father thought it necessary for the

00:33.160 --> 00:38.420
completion of my education that I should be made acquainted with other customs than those

00:38.420 --> 00:39.620
of my native country.

00:40.680 --> 00:45.680
My departure was therefore fixed at an early date, but before the day resolved upon could

00:45.680 --> 00:52.620
arrive, the first misfortune of my life occurred—an omen, as it were, of my future misery.

00:53.660 --> 00:59.000
Elizabeth had caught the scarlet fever, her illness was severe, and she was in the greatest

00:59.000 --> 01:04.920
danger. During her illness, many arguments had been urged to persuade my mother to refrain

01:04.920 --> 01:11.140
from attending upon her. She had at first yielded to her entreaties, but when she heard

01:11.140 --> 01:15.860
that the life of her favorites was menaced, she could no longer control her anxiety.

01:17.260 --> 01:22.380
She attended her sickbed, her watchful attentions triumphed over the malignity of the

01:22.380 --> 01:28.540
temper. Elizabeth was saved, but the consequences of this imprudence were fatal to her

01:28.540 --> 01:34.740
preserver. On the third day, my mother sickened. Her fever was accompanied by the most alarming

01:34.740 --> 01:41.700
symptoms, and the looks of her medical attendants prognosticated the worst event. On her

01:41.700 --> 01:47.900
deathbed, the fortitude and benignity of this best of women did not desert her. She joined

01:47.900 --> 01:49.620
the hands of Elizabeth and myself.

01:50.460 --> 01:56.420
My children, she said, my firmest hopes of future happiness were placed in the prospect

01:56.420 --> 02:02.220
of your union. This expectation will now be the consolation of your father. Elizabeth,

02:02.280 --> 02:09.580
my love, you must supply my place to my younger children. Alas, I regret that I am taken from

02:09.580 --> 02:17.000
you. And, happy and beloved as I have been, is it not hard to quit you all? But these

02:17.000 --> 02:22.560
are not thoughts befitting me. I will endeavour to resign myself cheerfully to death, and

02:22.560 --> 02:29.020
will indulge a hope of meeting you in another world. She died calmly, and her countenance

02:29.020 --> 02:34.680
expressed affection even in death. I need not describe the feelings of those whose dearest

02:34.680 --> 02:39.860
ties are rent by that most irreparable evil, the void that presents itself to the soul

02:39.860 --> 02:45.620
and the despair that is exhibited on the countenance. It is so long before the mind can persuade

02:45.620 --> 02:51.560
itself that she whom we saw every day, and whose very existence appeared part of our own,

02:51.840 --> 02:56.900
can have departed forever, that the brightness of a beloved eye can have been extinguished,

02:57.100 --> 03:02.880
and the sound of a voice so familiar and dear to the ear can be hushed, never more to be heard.

03:03.740 --> 03:09.180
These are the reflections of the first days. But when the lapse of time proves the reality

03:09.180 --> 03:15.820
of the evil, then the actual bitterness of grief commences. Yet from whom has not the

03:15.820 --> 03:21.360
rude hand rent away some dear connection? And why should I describe a sorrow which all have

03:21.360 --> 03:27.200
felt and must feel? The time at length arrives when grief is rather an indulgence than a

03:27.200 --> 03:32.340
necessity, and the smile that plays upon the lips, although it may be deemed a sacrilege,

03:32.620 --> 03:38.160
is not banished. My mother was dead, but we had still duties we ought to perform. We must

03:38.160 --> 03:43.640
continue our course with the rest, and learn to think ourselves fortunate whilst one remains

03:43.640 --> 03:50.200
whom the spoiler has not seized. My departure for Ingolstadt, which had been deferred by these

03:50.200 --> 03:56.900
events, was now again determined upon. I obtained from my father a respite of some weeks. It

03:56.900 --> 04:02.020
appeared to me sacrilege so soon to leave the repose akin to death of the house of mourning

04:02.020 --> 04:07.720
and to rush into the thick of life. I was new to sorrow, but it did not the less alarm me.

04:08.160 --> 04:13.800
I was unwilling to quit the sight of those that remained to me, and above all I desired to see my

04:13.800 --> 04:19.660
sweet Elizabeth in some degree consoled. She indeed veiled her grief, and strove to act the

04:19.660 --> 04:25.080
comforter to us all. She looked steadily on life, and assumed its duties with courage and zeal.

04:25.560 --> 04:29.860
She devoted herself to those whom she had been taught to call her uncle and cousins.

04:30.880 --> 04:36.140
Never was she so enchanting as at this time, when she recalled the sunshine of her smiles

04:36.140 --> 04:42.140
and spent them upon us. She forgot even her own regret in her endeavours to make us forget.

04:43.900 --> 04:49.020
The day of my departure at length arrived. Clairvaux spent the last evening with us.

04:49.460 --> 04:54.240
He had endeavoured to persuade his father to permit him to accompany me and to become my

04:54.240 --> 04:59.700
fellow student, but in vain. His father was a narrow-minded trader, and saw idleness and ruin

04:59.700 --> 05:04.800
in the aspirations and ambition of his son. Henry deeply felt the misfortune of being

05:04.800 --> 05:11.560
from a liberal education. He said little, but when he spoke, I read in his kindling eye and in his

05:11.560 --> 05:17.740
animated glance a restrained but firm resolve not to be chained to the miserable details of commerce.

05:18.520 --> 05:23.940
We sat late. We could not tear ourselves away from each other, nor persuade ourselves to say

05:23.940 --> 05:31.080
the word farewell. It was said, and we retired under the pretense of seeking repose, each fancying

05:31.080 --> 05:36.300
the other was deceived. But when, at morning's dawn, I descended to the carriage which was to

05:36.300 --> 05:42.420
convey me away, they were all there. My father, again to bless me, Clairvaux, to press my hand

05:42.420 --> 05:48.180
once more, my Elizabeth to renew her entreaties that I would write often and to bestow the last

05:48.180 --> 05:55.100
feminine attentions on her playmate and friend. I threw myself into the chaise that was to convey

05:55.100 --> 06:01.520
me away and indulge in the most melancholy reflections. I, who had ever been surrounded

06:01.520 --> 06:06.440
by amiable companions, continually engaged in endeavouring to bestow mutual pleasure.

06:07.160 --> 06:13.800
I was now alone. In the university whither I was going, I must form my own friends and be my own

06:13.800 --> 06:19.820
protector. My life had hitherto been remarkably secluded and domestic, and this had given me

06:19.820 --> 06:25.500
invincible repugnance to new countenances. I loved my brothers, Elizabeth and Clairvaux.

06:26.040 --> 06:30.940
These were old familiar faces, but I believed myself totally unfitted for the company of

06:30.940 --> 06:36.500
strangers. Such were my reflections as I commenced my journey. But as I proceeded,

06:36.940 --> 06:41.200
my spirits and hopes rose. I ardently desired the acquisition of knowledge.

06:41.880 --> 06:47.160
I had often, when at home, thought it hard to remain during my youth, cooped up in one place,

06:47.160 --> 06:52.540
and had longed to enter the world and take my station among other human beings. Now my desires

06:52.540 --> 06:59.040
were complied with, and it would indeed have been folly to repent. I had sufficient leisure for these

06:59.040 --> 07:04.000
and many other reflections during my journey to Ingolstadt, which was long and fatiguing.

07:04.200 --> 07:10.460
At length the high white steeple of the town met my eyes. I alighted and was conducted to my

07:10.460 --> 07:15.500
solitary apartment to spend the evening as I pleased. The next morning I delivered my

07:15.500 --> 07:21.860
introduction, and paid a visit to some of the principal professors. Chant, or rather the evil

07:21.860 --> 07:26.780
influence, the angel of destruction, which asserted omnipotent sway over me from the

07:26.780 --> 07:32.060
moment I turned my reluctant steps from my father's door, led me first to Monsieur Cramp,

07:32.580 --> 07:38.160
professor of natural philosophy. He was an uncouth man, but deeply imbued in the secrets

07:38.160 --> 07:43.180
of his science. He asked me several questions concerning my progress in the different branches

07:43.180 --> 07:48.980
of science appertaining to natural philosophy. I replied carelessly, and partly in contempt,

07:49.600 --> 07:53.140
mentioned the names of my alchemists as the principal authors I had studied.

07:53.900 --> 07:54.980
The professor stared.

07:55.920 --> 07:59.760
Have you, he said, really spent your time in studying such nonsense?

08:00.260 --> 08:01.560
I replied in the affirmative.

08:02.420 --> 08:07.680
Every minute, continued Monsieur Cramp with warmth, every instance that you have wasted

08:07.680 --> 08:13.660
on those books is utterly and entirely lost. You have burdened your memory with exploded

08:13.660 --> 08:20.320
systems and useless names. Good God! In what desert land have you lived where no one was

08:20.320 --> 08:25.520
kind enough to inform you that these fancies which you have so greedily imbibed are a thousand

08:25.520 --> 08:30.920
years old and as musty as they are ancient? I little expected, in this enlightened and

08:30.920 --> 08:36.840
scientific age, to find a disciple of Albertus Magnus and Paracelsus. My dear sir, you must

08:36.840 --> 08:42.220
begin your studies entirely anew. So saying, he stepped aside and wrote down a list of

08:42.220 --> 08:47.400
several books treating of natural philosophy which he desired me to procure, and dismissed

08:47.400 --> 08:51.660
me after mentioning that in the beginning of the following week he intended to commence

08:51.660 --> 08:56.140
a course of lectures upon natural philosophy in its general relations, and that Monsieur

08:56.140 --> 09:01.180
Voltmann, a fellow professor, would lecture upon chemistry the alternate days he omitted.

09:01.770 --> 09:06.860
I returned home not disappointed, for I have said that I had long considered those authors

09:06.860 --> 09:12.120
useless whom the professor reprobated, but I returned not at all the more inclined to

09:12.120 --> 09:17.640
recur to these studies in any shape. Monsieur Cramp was a little squat man with a gruff

09:17.640 --> 09:22.800
voice and a repulsive countenance. The teacher, therefore, did not prepossess me in favour of

09:22.800 --> 09:28.880
his pursuits. In rather a too philosophical and connected strain, perhaps, I have given

09:28.880 --> 09:34.380
an account of the conclusions I had come to concerning them in my early years. As a child,

09:34.640 --> 09:38.720
I had not been content with the results promised by the modern professors of natural science.

09:39.500 --> 09:44.720
With a confusion of ideas only to be accounted for by my extreme youth and my want of a guide

09:44.720 --> 09:50.480
on such matters, I had retrod the steps of knowledge along the paths of time and exchanged

09:50.480 --> 09:56.520
the discoveries of recent inquirers for the dreams of forgotten alchemists. Besides,

09:56.520 --> 10:01.940
I had a contempt for the uses of modern natural philosophy. It was very different when the masters

10:01.940 --> 10:09.020
of the science sought immortality and power. Such views, although futile, were grand. But now the

10:09.020 --> 10:15.100
scene was changed. The ambition of the inquirer seemed to limit itself to the annihilation of

10:15.100 --> 10:20.560
those visions on which my interest in the science was chiefly founded. I was required to exchange

10:20.560 --> 10:26.000
shimmers of boundless grandeur for realities of little worth. Such were my reflections during

10:26.000 --> 10:31.000
the first two or three days of my residence at Ingolstadt, which were chiefly spent in becoming

10:31.000 --> 10:36.020
acquainted with the localities and the principal residence in my new abode. But as the ensuing

10:36.020 --> 10:41.220
week commenced, I thought of the information which Mr. Cramp had given me concerning the lectures.

10:41.960 --> 10:47.220
And although I could not consent to go and hear that little conceited fellow deliver sentences

10:47.220 --> 10:52.940
out of the pulpit, I recollected what he had said of Mr. Waldman, whom I had never seen,

10:52.940 --> 10:57.880
as he had hitherto been out of town. Partly from curiosity and partly from idleness,

10:58.340 --> 11:02.200
I went into the lecturing room which Mr. Waldman entered shortly after.

11:02.900 --> 11:07.480
This professor was very unlike his colleague. He appeared about fifty years of age,

11:07.740 --> 11:12.700
but with an aspect expressive of the greatest benevolence. A few grey hairs covered his temples,

11:13.180 --> 11:19.480
but those at the back of his head were nearly black. His person was short but remarkably erect,

11:19.480 --> 11:25.240
and his voice the sweetest I had ever heard. He began his lecture by a recapitulation of the

11:25.240 --> 11:30.040
history of chemistry and the various improvements made by different men of learning, pronouncing

11:30.040 --> 11:35.700
with fervour the names of the most distinguished discoverers. He then took a cursory view of the

11:35.700 --> 11:41.460
present state of the science, and explained many of its elementary terms. After having made a few

11:41.460 --> 11:46.980
preparatory experiments, he concluded with a panegyric upon modern chemistry, the terms of

11:46.980 --> 11:48.260
which I shall never forget.

11:48.800 --> 11:54.980
The ancient teachers of this science, he said, promised impossibilities and performed nothing.

11:55.760 --> 12:01.480
The modern masters promise very little. They know that metals cannot be transmuted,

12:01.620 --> 12:07.880
and that the excelsior of life is a shimmerer. But these philosophers, whose hands seem only

12:07.880 --> 12:12.340
made to dabble in dirt, and their eyes to pour over the microscope or crucible,

12:12.900 --> 12:18.100
have indeed performed miracles. They penetrate into the recesses of nature,

12:18.600 --> 12:24.720
and show how she walks in our hiding places. They ascend into the heavens. They have discovered how

12:24.720 --> 12:30.660
the blood circulates, and the nature of the air we breathe. They have acquired new and almost

12:30.660 --> 12:37.100
unlimited powers. They can command the thunders of heaven, mimic the earthquake, and even mock

12:37.100 --> 12:39.260
the invisible world with its own shadows.

12:40.260 --> 12:46.180
Such were the professor's words. Rather let me say, such the words of the fate announced to

12:46.180 --> 12:51.980
destroy me. As he went on, I felt as if my soul were grappling with a palpable enemy.

12:52.500 --> 12:56.980
One by one the various keys were touched which formed the mechanism of my being.

12:57.800 --> 13:02.020
Chord after chord were sounded, and soon my mind was filled with one thought,

13:02.020 --> 13:04.140
one conception, one purpose.

13:04.860 --> 13:10.840
So much has been done, exclaimed the soul of Frankenstein. More, far more will I achieve.

13:11.600 --> 13:14.860
Treading in the steps already marked, I will pioneer a new way,

13:15.200 --> 13:19.600
explore unknown powers, and unfold to the world the deepest mysteries of creation.

13:20.940 --> 13:26.700
I closed my eyes that night. My internal being was in a state of insurrection and turmoil.

13:27.160 --> 13:31.380
I felt that order would thence arise, but I had no power to produce it.

13:32.020 --> 13:38.040
By degrees, after the morning's dawn, sleep came. I awoke, and my yesternight's thoughts

13:38.040 --> 13:42.880
were as a dream. There only remained a resolution to return to my ancient studies,

13:43.280 --> 13:48.120
and to devote myself to a science for which I believe myself to possess a natural talent.

13:48.860 --> 13:54.320
On the same day I paid Monsieur Waldemann a visit. His manners in private were even more

13:54.320 --> 13:59.480
mild and attractive than in public, for there was a certain dignity in his mane during his lectures,

13:59.480 --> 14:03.280
which in his own house was replaced by the greatest affability and kindness.

14:03.740 --> 14:08.640
I gave him pretty nearly the same account of my former pursuits as I had given his fellow

14:08.640 --> 14:14.180
professor. He heard with attention the little narration concerning my studies, and smiled at

14:14.180 --> 14:19.660
the names of Cornelius Agrippa and Paracelsus, but without the contempt that Monsieur Cramp had

14:19.660 --> 14:26.200
exhibited. He said that these were men to whose indefatigable zeal modern philosophers were

14:26.200 --> 14:32.700
indebted for most of the foundations of their knowledge. They had left to us, as an easier task,

14:33.000 --> 14:38.460
to give new names and arrange in connected classifications the facts which they, in a

14:38.460 --> 14:44.060
great degree, had been the instruments of bringing to light. The labours of men of genius,

14:44.580 --> 14:51.080
however erroneously directed, scarcely ever fail in ultimately turning to the solid advantage of

14:51.080 --> 14:56.920
I listened to a statement which was delivered without any presumption or affectation,

14:57.200 --> 15:01.540
and then added that his lecture had removed my prejudice against modern chemists.

15:02.060 --> 15:06.100
I expressed myself in measured terms, with the modesty and deference

15:06.100 --> 15:11.000
due from a youth to his instructor, without letting escape. An experience in life would

15:11.000 --> 15:15.840
have made me ashamed. Any of the enthusiasm which stimulated my intended labours.

15:16.480 --> 15:19.700
I requested his advice concerning books I ought to procure.

15:20.400 --> 15:26.000
I am happy, said Monsieur Voltman, to have gained a disciple, and if your application

15:26.000 --> 15:32.120
equals your ability, I have no doubt of your success. Chemistry is that branch of natural

15:32.120 --> 15:37.860
philosophy in which the greatest improvements have been and may be made. It is on that account

15:37.860 --> 15:44.260
that I have made it my peculiar study. But at the same time I have not neglected the other branches

15:44.260 --> 15:50.860
of science. A man would make a very sorry chemist if he attended to that department

15:50.860 --> 15:57.220
of human knowledge alone. If your wish is to become really a man of science, and not merely

15:57.220 --> 16:02.460
a petty experimentalist, I would advise you to apply to every branch of natural philosophy,

16:02.800 --> 16:08.260
including mathematics. He then took me into his laboratory and explained to me the uses

16:08.260 --> 16:13.580
of his various machines, instructing me as to what I ought to procure, and promising me

16:13.580 --> 16:18.600
use of his own when I should have advanced far enough in the science not to derange the mechanism.

16:19.280 --> 16:23.060
He also gave me a list of books which I had requested, and I took my leave.

16:23.880 --> 16:28.140
Thus ended a day memorable to me. It decided my future destiny.

16:29.500 --> 16:30.540
CHAPTER IV

16:31.100 --> 16:36.140
From this day natural philosophy, and particularly chemistry, in the most comprehensive sense of the

16:36.140 --> 16:41.500
term, became nearly my sole occupation. I read with ardour those works so full of genius and

16:41.500 --> 16:46.340
discrimination which modern inquirers have written on these subjects. I attended the

16:46.340 --> 16:51.280
lectures and cultivated the acquaintance of the men of science of the University, and found even

16:51.280 --> 16:57.140
in Mr. Cramp a great deal of sound sense and real information, combined as is true with a repulsive

16:57.140 --> 17:03.580
physiognomy and manners, but not, on that account, the less valuable. In Mr. Waltman I found a true

17:03.580 --> 17:08.500
friend. His gentleness was never tinged by dogmatism, and his instructions were given

17:08.500 --> 17:14.520
an air of frankness and good nature that banished every idea of pedantry. In a thousand ways he

17:14.520 --> 17:19.980
smoothed for me the path of knowledge and made the most abstruse inquiries clear and facile to my

17:19.980 --> 17:25.280
apprehension. My application was at first fluctuating and uncertain. It gained strength

17:25.280 --> 17:30.320
as I proceeded, and soon became so ardent and eager that the stars often disappeared

17:30.320 --> 17:37.080
in the light of morning, whilst I was yet engaged in my laboratory. As I applied so closely,

17:37.080 --> 17:42.520
may be easily conceived that my progress was rapid. My ardour was indeed the astonishment

17:42.520 --> 17:48.520
of the students, and my proficiency that of the masters. Professor Cramp often asked me,

17:48.520 --> 17:54.000
with a sly smile, how Cornelius Agrippa went on, whilst Monsieur Waltman expressed the most

17:54.000 --> 17:59.700
heartfelt exaltation in my progress. Two years passed in this manner, during which I paid no

17:59.700 --> 18:05.260
visit to Geneva, but was engaged, heart and soul, in the pursuit of some discoveries which I hoped

18:05.260 --> 18:11.240
to make. None but those who have experienced them can conceive of the enticements of science.

18:12.160 --> 18:17.280
In other studies you go as far as others have gone before you, and there is nothing more to know,

18:17.700 --> 18:23.440
but in scientific pursuit there is continual food for discovery and wonder. A mind of moderate

18:23.440 --> 18:29.300
capacity which closely pursues one study must infallibly arrive at great proficiency in that

18:29.300 --> 18:35.620
I, who continually sought the attainment of one object of pursuit and was solely wrapped up in

18:35.620 --> 18:41.920
this, improved so rapidly that at the end of two years I made some discoveries in the improvement

18:41.920 --> 18:47.880
of some chemical instrument which procured me great esteem and admiration at the university.

18:48.640 --> 18:53.200
When I had arrived at this point and had become as well acquainted with the theory and practice of

18:53.200 --> 18:58.840
natural philosophy as depended on the lessons of any of the professors at Ingolstadt, my residence

18:58.840 --> 19:04.420
there being no longer conducive to my improvement, I thought of returning to my friends and my native

19:04.420 --> 19:11.060
town when an incident happened that protracted my stay. One of the phenomena which had peculiarly

19:11.060 --> 19:18.020
attracted my attention was the structure of the human frame, and indeed any animal endued with life.

19:19.080 --> 19:25.220
Whence, I often ask myself, did the principle of life proceed? It was a bold question and one which

19:25.220 --> 19:31.020
has ever been considered as a mystery. Yet with how many things are we upon the brink of becoming

19:31.020 --> 19:37.420
acquainted if cowardice or carelessness did not restrain our inquiries? I resolved these

19:37.420 --> 19:43.500
circumstances in my mind and determined henceforth to apply myself more particularly to those branches

19:43.500 --> 19:49.920
of natural philosophy which related to physiology. Unless I had been animated by an almost supernatural

19:49.920 --> 19:55.020
enthusiasm, my application to this study would have been irksome and almost intolerable.

19:55.220 --> 20:01.680
To examine the causes of life we must first have recourse to death. I became acquainted with the

20:01.680 --> 20:07.720
science of anatomy, but this was not sufficient. I must also observe the natural decay and corruption

20:07.720 --> 20:14.180
of the human body. In my education my father had taken the greatest precautions that my mind should

20:14.180 --> 20:24.520
be impressed with no supernatural horrors. I do not even remember to have trembled at a tale of

20:24.520 --> 20:30.340
The darkness had no effect upon my fancy, and a churchyard was to me merely the receptacle of bodies

20:30.340 --> 20:37.240
deprived of life, which, from being the seat of beauty and strength, had become food for the worm.

20:38.200 --> 20:43.160
Now I was led to examine the cause and the progress of this decay and forced to spend

20:43.160 --> 20:48.920
days and nights in vaults and charnel houses. My attention was fixed upon every object the

20:48.920 --> 20:55.120
most insupportable to the delicacy of human feelings. I saw how the fine form of man was

20:55.120 --> 21:00.520
degraded and wasted. I beheld the corruption of death succeed to the blooming cheek of life.

21:00.800 --> 21:07.000
I saw how the worm inherited the wonders of the eye and the brain. I paused, examining and analyzing

21:07.000 --> 21:13.700
all the minutiae of causation as exemplified in the change from life to death and death to life,

21:13.700 --> 21:19.960
until, from the midst of this darkness, a sudden light broke in upon me—a light so brilliant

21:19.960 --> 21:25.600
and wondrous, yet so simple, that while I became dizzy with the immensity of the prospect which it

21:25.600 --> 21:31.540
illuminated, I was surprised that among so many men of genius who had directed their inquiries

21:31.540 --> 21:36.960
towards the same science, that I alone should be reserved to discover so astonishing a secret.

21:37.680 --> 21:43.800
Remember, I am not recording the vision of a madman. The sun does not more certainly

21:43.800 --> 21:49.340
shine in the heavens than that which I now affirm is true. Some miracle might have produced it,

21:49.460 --> 21:54.500
yet the stages of the discovery were distinct and probable. After days and nights of incredible

21:54.500 --> 22:00.440
labour and fatigue, I succeeded in discovering the cause of generation and life. Nay, more,

22:00.660 --> 22:04.500
I became myself capable of bestowing animation upon lifeless matter.

22:05.300 --> 22:10.940
The astonishment which I had at first experienced on this discovery soon gave place to delight in

22:10.940 --> 22:16.560
rapture. After so much time spent in painful labour, to arrive at once at the summit of my

22:16.560 --> 22:21.860
desires was the most gratifying consummation of my toils. But this discovery was so great

22:21.860 --> 22:27.040
and overwhelming that all the steps by which I had been progressively led to it were obliterated,

22:27.200 --> 22:32.700
and I beheld only the result. What had been the study and desire of the wisest men since

22:32.700 --> 22:39.920
creation of the world was now within my grasp. Not that, like a magic scene, it all opened upon

22:39.920 --> 22:45.660
me at once. The information I had obtained was of a nature rather to direct my endeavours so soon as

22:45.660 --> 22:50.040
I should point them towards the object of my search than to exhibit that object already

22:50.040 --> 22:55.800
accomplished. I was like the Arabian who had been buried with the dead and found a passage to life

22:55.800 --> 23:01.420
aided only by one glimmering and seemingly ineffectual light. I see by your eagerness

23:01.420 --> 23:07.000
and the wonder and hope which your eyes express, my friend, that you expect to be informed of the

23:07.000 --> 23:13.240
secret with which I am acquainted. That cannot be. Listen patiently until the end of my story,

23:13.400 --> 23:19.320
and you will easily perceive why I am so reserved on that subject. I will not lead you on,

23:19.540 --> 23:25.620
unguarded and ardent, as I then was, to your destruction and infallible misery. Learn from

23:25.620 --> 23:32.600
me, if not by my precepts, at least by my example, how dangerous is the acquirement of knowledge and

23:32.600 --> 23:38.080
how much happier that man is who believes his native town to be the world than he who aspires

23:38.080 --> 23:43.600
to become greater than his nature will allow. When I found so astonishing a power placed within my

23:43.600 --> 23:48.360
hands, I hesitated a long time concerning the manner in which I should employ it.

23:48.780 --> 23:54.220
Although I possessed the capacity of bestowing life, yet to prepare a frame for the reception

23:54.220 --> 23:59.840
of it, with all its intricacies of fibres, muscles and veins, still remained a work of

23:59.840 --> 24:05.240
inconceivable difficulty and labour. I doubted at first whether I should attempt the creation

24:05.240 --> 24:11.140
of a being like myself, or one of simpler organisation, but my imagination was too much

24:11.140 --> 24:16.140
exalted by my first success to permit me to doubt of my ability to give life to an animal

24:16.140 --> 24:21.740
as complex and wonderful as man. The materials at present within my command hardly appeared

24:21.740 --> 24:26.860
adequate to so arduous an undertaking, but I doubted not that I should ultimately succeed.

24:27.320 --> 24:32.840
I prepared myself for a multitude of reverses. My operations might be incessantly baffled,

24:33.060 --> 24:38.080
and at last my work be imperfect, yet when I considered the improvement which every day

24:38.080 --> 24:43.220
takes place in science and mechanics, I was encouraged to hope my present attempts would

24:43.220 --> 24:48.860
at least lay the foundations of future success. Nor could I consider the magnitude and complexity

24:48.860 --> 24:55.500
of my plan as any argument of its impracticability. It was with these feelings that I began the

24:55.500 --> 25:01.320
creation of a human being. As the minuteness of the parts formed a great hindrance to my speed,

25:01.840 --> 25:07.980
I resolved, contrary to my first intention, to make a being of gigantic stature, that is to say,

25:08.180 --> 25:13.820
about eight feet in height and proportionally large. After having formed this determination

25:13.820 --> 25:18.080
and having spent some months in successfully collecting and arranging my materials,

25:18.080 --> 25:23.400
I began. No one can conceive the variety of feelings which bore me onwards,

25:24.480 --> 25:30.060
like a hurricane in the first enthusiasm of success. Life and death appeared to me ideal

25:30.060 --> 25:35.560
bounds which I should break through and pour a torrent of light into our dark world. A new

25:35.560 --> 25:41.180
species would bless me as its creator and source. Many happy and excellent natures would owe their

25:41.180 --> 25:46.880
being to me. No father could claim the gratitude of his child so completely as I should deserve

25:47.540 --> 25:52.900
pursuing these reflections. I thought that if I could bestow animation upon lifeless matter,

25:53.400 --> 25:58.740
I might in process of time, although I now found it impossible, to renew life where death had

25:58.740 --> 26:05.080
apparently devoted the body to corruption. These thoughts supported my spirits while I pursued my

26:05.080 --> 26:11.040
undertaking with unremitting ardour. My cheek had grown pale with study and my person had become

26:11.040 --> 26:18.220
emaciated with confinement. Sometimes, on the very brink of certainty, I failed. Yet still I

26:18.220 --> 26:24.940
clung to the hope which the next day or the next hour might realise. One secret which I alone

26:24.940 --> 26:31.420
possessed was the hope to which I had dedicated myself, and the moon gazed on my midnight labours

26:31.420 --> 26:36.780
while, with unrelaxed and breathless eagerness, I pursued nature to her hiding places.

26:37.440 --> 26:43.340
Who shall conceive the horrors of my secret toil as I dabbled among the unhallowed damps of the

26:43.340 --> 26:50.100
grave or tortured the living animal to animate the lifeless clay? My limbs now tremble and my

26:50.100 --> 26:55.400
eyes swim with the remembrance, but then a resistless and almost frantic impulse urged

26:55.400 --> 27:01.360
me forward. I seem to have lost all soul or sensation but for this one pursuit.

27:01.960 --> 27:08.800
It was indeed but a passing trance that only made me feel with renewed acuteness so soon as

27:08.800 --> 27:13.340
the unnatural stimulus ceasing to operate. I had returned to my old habits.

27:14.620 --> 27:20.780
I collected bones from the charnel houses and disturbed with profane fingers the tremendous

27:20.780 --> 27:27.040
secrets of the human frame, in a solitary chamber or other cell at the top of the house,

27:27.040 --> 27:31.420
and separated from all the other apartments by a gallery and staircase,

27:31.920 --> 27:37.520
I kept my workshop of filthy creation. My eyeballs were starting from their sockets

27:37.520 --> 27:42.940
and attending to the details of my employment. The dissecting room and the slaughterhouse

27:42.940 --> 27:49.400
furnished many of my materials, and often did my human nature turn with loathing from my occupation.

27:49.880 --> 27:55.900
While still urged on by an eagerness which perpetually increased, I brought my work near

27:55.900 --> 28:00.220
to a conclusion. The summer months passed while I was thus engaged, half and soul,

28:00.260 --> 28:05.440
in one pursuit. It was a most beautiful season, never did the fields bestow a more plentiful

28:05.440 --> 28:10.320
harvest or the vines yield a more luxuriant vintage. I brought my work near to a conclusion.

28:10.900 --> 28:15.240
The summer months passed while I was thus engaged, half and soul, in one pursuit. It

28:15.240 --> 28:19.900
was a most beautiful season, never did the fields bestow a more plentiful harvest nor

28:19.900 --> 28:25.220
the vines yield a luxurious vintage, but my eyes were insensible to the charms of nature.

28:25.900 --> 28:30.260
And the same feelings which made me neglect the scenes around me caused me also to forget

28:30.260 --> 28:35.560
those friends who were so many miles absent, and whom I had not seen for so long a time.

28:36.360 --> 28:40.880
I knew my silence disquieted them, and I well remembered the words of my father.

28:41.640 --> 28:47.200
I know that while you are pleased with yourself you will think of us with affection, and we

28:47.200 --> 28:48.700
shall hear regularly from you.

28:49.160 --> 28:54.800
You must pardon me if I regard any interruption in your correspondence as a proof that your

28:54.800 --> 28:56.380
other duties are equally neglected.

28:57.580 --> 29:02.360
I knew well, therefore, what would be my father's feelings, but I could not tear my thoughts

29:02.360 --> 29:07.580
from my employment, loathsome in itself, but which had taken an irresistible hold of my

29:07.580 --> 29:08.120
imagination.

29:09.040 --> 29:13.920
I wished, as it were, to procrastinate all that related to my feelings of affection until

29:13.920 --> 29:18.580
the great object, which swallowed up every habit of my nature, should be completed.

29:19.360 --> 29:25.440
I then thought my father would be unjust if he ascribed my neglect to vice or faultiness

29:25.440 --> 29:30.160
on my part, but I am now convinced that he was justified in conceiving that I should

29:30.160 --> 29:31.940
not be altogether free from blame.

29:32.920 --> 29:38.300
A human being in perfection ought always to preserve a calm and peaceful mind, and never

29:38.300 --> 29:42.500
allow passion or a transitory desire to disturb his tranquillity.

29:43.420 --> 29:46.820
I do not think that the pursuit of knowledge is an exception to this rule.

29:47.460 --> 29:52.140
If the study to which you apply yourself has a tendency to weaken your affections and to

29:52.140 --> 29:57.900
destroy your taste for those simple pleasures in which no alloy can possibly mix, then that

29:57.900 --> 30:03.020
study is certainly unlawful, that is to say, not befitting the human mind.

30:04.120 --> 30:09.500
If this rule were always observed, if no man allowed any pursuit whatsoever to interfere

30:09.500 --> 30:15.640
with the tranquillity of his domestic affections, Greece had not been enslaved, Caesar would

30:15.640 --> 30:20.760
have spared his country, America would have been discovered more gradually, and the empires

30:20.760 --> 30:23.400
of Mexico and Peru had not been destroyed.

30:25.420 --> 30:29.800
But I forget that I am moralizing in the most interesting part of my tale, and your looks

30:29.800 --> 30:30.820
remind me to proceed.

30:32.080 --> 30:37.200
My father made no reproach in his letters, and only took notice of my silence by inquiring

30:37.200 --> 30:39.860
into my occupations more particularly than before.

30:40.560 --> 30:45.700
Winter, spring, and summer passed away during my labours, but I did not watch the blossom

30:45.700 --> 30:52.400
on the expanding leaves, sights which before always yielded me supreme delight, so deeply

30:52.400 --> 30:54.000
was I engrossed in my occupation.

30:55.360 --> 31:01.020
The leaves of that year had withered before my work drew near a close, and now every day

31:01.020 --> 31:03.380
showed me more plainly how well I had succeeded.

31:04.380 --> 31:09.560
But my enthusiasm was checked by my anxiety, and I appeared rather like one doomed by

31:09.560 --> 31:15.560
slavery to toil in the mines, or any other unwholesome trade, than an artist occupied

31:15.560 --> 31:16.780
by his favourite employment.

31:17.540 --> 31:22.620
Every night I was oppressed by a slow fever, and I became nervous to a most painful degree.

31:23.300 --> 31:27.800
The fall of a leaf startled me, and I shunned my fellow creatures as if I had been guilty

31:27.800 --> 31:28.460
of a crime.

31:28.460 --> 31:35.520
Sometimes I grew alarmed at the wreck I perceived that I had become, and the energy of my purpose

31:35.520 --> 31:36.800
alone sustained me.

31:37.480 --> 31:41.640
My labours would soon end, and I believed that exercise and amusement would then drive

31:41.640 --> 31:46.880
away incipient disease, and I promised myself both of these when my creation should be complete.

